    <!-- Ground-level textured tiles (Phase 3 Milestone B landing-divergence
         fix, 2026-07-09; RE-COLORED 2026-07-10 — see below) — root-caused a
         real AUTO_LAND flyaway to visual feature starvation near the
         ground: the fence props above are TALL (0.7-1.6m), and at low
         altitude near the landing point their tops exit the D435i's 42 deg
         vertical FOV, leaving only this world's flat, uniform-gray
         ground_plane in view — zero texture gradient, zero KLT corners, so
         OpenVINS loses all feature tracks exactly during descent/touchdown
         and falls back to unconstrained IMU dead-reckoning. Real ground
         surfaces (grass, asphalt, carpet) always have texture; this
         uniform gray plane did not. These are thin (1cm), ground-level
         1x1m boxes (NOT a Gazebo material/texture asset — same technique
         as the fence props above, guaranteed to render with no missing-
         asset risk) covering an 8x8m grid under the whole mission
         footprint and landing point, so the tracker has real ground-level
         corners in view at any altitude, including touchdown.

         RE-COLORED 2026-07-10: the original version alternated exactly 2
         shades in a strict checkerboard — every tile corner in the grid was
         locally indistinguishable from every other, a textbook aliasing
         trap for a corner tracker (the KLT tracker/RANSAC associating a
         feature with the WRONG grid corner, since they all look identical
         nearby) flagged as a likely contributor to inconsistent flight
         behavior across otherwise-identical runs: resource/
         Vio_Drift_analysis.txt. Each tile's shade below is now a fixed,
         deterministic (not literally random, so this file stays
         reproducible) hash of its grid indices across an 8-color palette —
         still zero missing-asset risk, but no periodic pattern for a
         tracker to alias against. See DEVELOPMENT_STATUS.md "Milestone B
         result, part 7" for the original landing-divergence incident this
         tile grid was added to fix. -->
